  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Postface to the Ten Admonitions on the Great Learning
  author: Yu Sun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Observing now the Ten Admonitions on the Great Learning and their exposition of beginning and end, I see that their fountainhead is pure, their reasoning true, their elaboration thorough and complete. What sacred words these are! Among the writings on Principle and Nature in our Eastern realm, such work has been absent since Yang-chon, appearing now as rare treasure returned. Recently, through what my son conveyed, I received the command—unworthy though I am—to polish and refine these words. I dare not accept such honor.

    In my youth I abandoned learning for office. For more than ten years after entering service, I labored with brush and seal. Late in life I was undeservedly granted the position of scribe, and though I have occasionally engaged with letters, I have merely scratched surfaces and carved forms. Regarding the learning of Principle and Nature itself, I have grown old without reaching it.

    The Master's learning runs deep as fathomless springs; his understanding of Principle is perfected and settled. In composing this work, he intends to present it during royal discourse, to serve as a mirror for the ruler's heart. His expression of purpose is crystalline, beyond reproach. How dare I venture to comment?

    Old age and illness weigh upon me; my steps falter. I have long yearned to attend the lecture hall but cannot. This has been my lifelong sorrow. Yet now, having obtained the Master's writing and read it again and again, I suddenly find myself seated at the lecturer's side, hearing his discourse. What fortune!

    Our Sage-King now turns his heart toward the Way and seeks to perfect the Highest Principle. Surely he will savor the Master's words, deeply comprehend the Way of the Great Learning, and put into practice the investigation of things and extension of knowledge, sincerity of intention and rectification of mind. With the source clarified and governance perfected, his sagely power and transformative influence shall reach their zenith, and the age of harmony and peace shall be achieved. Thus the Master's years of diligent teaching and today's sincere offering of loyal service shall find their fulfillment. Yu Sun cannot contain his fervent hope. With utmost respect, I write this.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yang-chon (陽村) refers to the late Goryeo Neo-Confucian scholar who represents the period after which such philosophical writings on Principle and Nature became rare in the Korean tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Ten Admonitions on the Great Learning' refers to a work of political philosophy based on the classical Confucian text, structured as ten moral injunctions.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'lecture hall' (講席) and 'royal discourse' (經筵) reference the formal scholarly institutions where the king would receive instruction in classical learning and virtue.
